04592nam a22006855i 9781575063683DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20212015pau    fo  d z      eng d  a2015014152  a97815750636837 a10.1515/97815750636832doi  a(DE-B1597)584485  a(OCoLC)1266229598  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA00aBS651b.M396 2015 4aBS651 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a222/.1106223/eng1 aMcDowell, Catherine L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Image of God in the Garden of Eden :bThe Creation of Humankind in Genesis 2:5-3:24 in Light of the mīs pî, pīt pî, and wpt-r Rituals of Mesopotamia and Ancient Egypt /cCatherine L. McDowell. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSiphrut: Literature and Theology of the Hebrew Scriptures ;v150 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCatherine McDowell presents a detailed and insightful analysis of the creation of adam in Gen 2:5-3:24 in light of the Mesopotamian mīs pî pīt pî ("washing of the mouth, opening of the mouth") and the Egyptian wpt-r (opening of the mouth) rituals for the creation of a divine image. Parallels between the mouth washing and opening rituals and the Eden story suggest that the biblical author was comparing and contrasting human creation with the ritual creation, animation, and installation of a cult statue in order to redefine ṣelem F2;elohîm as a human being-the living likeness of God tending and serving in the sacred garden.McDowell also considers the explicit image and likeness language in Gen 1:26-27. Drawing from biblical and extrabiblical texts, she demonstrates that ṣelem and demût define the divine-human relationship, first and foremost, in terms of kinship. To be created in the image and likeness of Elohim was to be, metaphorically speaking, God's royal sons and daughters. While these royal qualities are explicit in Gen 1, McDowell persuasively argues that kinship is the primary metaphor Gen 1 uses to define humanity and its relationship to God.Further, she discusses critical issues, noting the problems inherent in the traditional views on the dating and authorship of Gen 1-3, and the relationship between the two creation accounts. Through a careful study of the tôledôt in Genesis, she demonstrates that Gen 2:4 serves as both a hinge and a "telescope": the creation of humanity in Gen 2:5-3:24 should be understood as a detailed account of the events of Day 6 in Gen 1.When Gen 1-3 are read together, as the final redactor intended, these texts redefine the divine-human relationship using three significant and theologically laden categories: kinship, kingship, and cult. Thus, they provide an important lens through which to view the relationship between God and humanity as presented in the rest of the Bible.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aCreationxBiblical teaching. 0aImage of GodxBiblical teaching. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311074525240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781575063683?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781575063683423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781575063683/original  a978-3-11-074525-2  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK